Oh. Oh lord. I'm a protein scientist with a serious dissociative disorder, and I wasn't expecting to get made into a SCP. Huh. Dr Rydderech is so eerily relatable that I actually got some secondhand dissociation from reading his stuff. Or maybe my memories are lying… I don't know. I'm excited to read this again when I inevitably forget it exists in a few days, months, and years, repeatedly. I wonder if it'll feel any different in the distant future. The feeling of  will be palpable, but it was already palpable this time, and I don't think I've already read it, since it's only two months old…

+block

–block


Um but yes, I don't do toxicology exactly (it's hard to say what I do… my coworkers are working on enzymes that stop a virus, but the support I provide is very abstract), but, 

Sorry, I'm usually a little more coherent than this, I'm just not very present right now. I'm not sure if it's a result of reading the article. I read it between several minutes and several hours ago and that should be plenty of time to recover. But it's hard to determine cause and effect even on the best day, so I won't think about it too hard. I appreciate this article and I'll be sure to stumble upon the related tale eventually, when you write it.

edit: Upon further review and a slow drift towards lucidity, I came up with the idea of perhaps writing a tale from the perspective of this guy? Or maybe just drawing him, that seems more difficult to get offensively wrong. It would be roughly my first ever time drawing a human(oid) so it would be interesting. But maybe if it were possible for me to do that, I'd have done it by now, instead of apparently flaking out every time. Then again I only (re?)discovered my ability to draw this April. Sorry for rambling about dissociative stuff again, I'm just still so surprised to be  like this, and I still feel compelled to share aspects of my life experience that align with what's represented in the article. Like, I thought qntm/sam512/Sam Hughes's antimemetics stuff represented my life well, what with the antimemetics researchers always having to assume they're forgetting everything, and developing inviolable rules to compensate for that, exactly as I've done, but… this is really on another level. (Or maybe I'm just not remembering/appreciating properly how impressed I was at Sam Hughes's stuff. That's always possible.)

edit 2: Oh also, no comment on the whole issue of leaving Dr Rydderech alive. Since Dr Scout knew him well for a very long time and was able to interpret his testimonials, I guess I'd go with what he said. But as someone who's a lot closer to SCP-5520 than they are to Dr Rydderech, I'm not allowing myself to entertain the idea that maybe it is better to be dead than what I am right now, which is something I struggle to reject rationally, and instead just reject categorically to save time and brain effort. Dr Rydderech is fictional and I'm only slightly less fictional, so… I'm not actually sure what point I was going to make with that, sorry. Anyway I don't feel like dying at the moment so I will refrain from further commentary.

edit 3: wait actually i remembered some legitimate reasons to live, and some things about my future that are predictable, even predictably positive. i don't remember the article anymore though so i still won't comment. sorry again.




